Plug-in name: Eva
Plug-in shortname: eva
Description:
automatically computes variation domains for the variables of the program

Most options of the form '-eva-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-eva-no-option-name'.

Most options of the form '-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-no-option-name'.

Options taking a string as argument should preferably be written
-option-name="argument".

***** LIST OF AVAILABLE OPTIONS:

-eva                Run the Eva analysis. (opposite option is -no-eva)
-val                alias for option -eva
-eva-precision <n>  Meta-option that automatically sets up some Eva
                    parameters for a quick configuration of an analysis, from
                    0 (fastest but rather imprecise analysis) to 11 (accurate
                    but potentially slow analysis).

*** ABSTRACT DOMAINS

-eva-domains <d1,...,dn>  Enable a list of analysis domains. Available
                    domains are: cvalue, equality, symbolic-locations,
                    gauges, octagon, multidim, bitwise, taint, numerors,
                    sign, mthread, inout, printer, traces. Use -eva-domains
                    help to print a short description of each domain.
-eva-domains-function <d:f>  Enable a domain only for the given functions.
                    <d:f+> enables the domain [d] from function [f] (the
                    domain is enabled in all functions called from [f]).
                    <d:f-> disables the domain [d] from function [f].
                    (preferably use -eva-domains-function="d:f")
-eva-equality-through-calls <none|formals|all>  Propagate equalities through
                    function calls (from the caller to the called function):
                    none, only equalities between formal parameters and
                    concrete arguments, or all.  (preferably use
                    -eva-equality-through-calls="none|formals|all")
-eva-equality-through-calls-function <f:none|formals|all>  Propagate
                    equalities through calls to specific functions. Overrides
                    -eva-equality-call. (preferably use
                    -eva-equality-through-calls-function="f:none|formals|all")
-eva-multidim-disjunctive-invariants  Try to infer structures disjunctive
                    invariants. (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-multidim-disjunctive-invariants)
-eva-multidim-segment-limit <N>  Limit the number of segments in the
                    abstraction of arrays.
-eva-numerors-interaction <relative|absolute|none|both>  Define how the
                    numerors domain infers the absolute and the relative
                    errors:
                    - relative: the relative is deduced from the absolute;
                    - absolute: the absolute is deduced from the relative;
                    - none: absolute and relative are computed separately;
                    - both: reduced product between absolute and relative.
                    (preferably use
                    -eva-numerors-interaction="relative|absolute|none|both")
-eva-octagon-through-calls  Propagate relations inferred by the octagon
                    domain through function calls. Disabled by default: the
                    octagon analysis is intra-procedural, starting each
                    function with an empty octagon state, and losing the
                    octagons inferred at the end. The interprocedural
                    analysis is more precise but slower. (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-octagon-through-calls)
-eva-secure-flow    Perform secure-flow analysis to prove non-interference
                    properties: emit warnings whenever low-security public
                    data may depend on high-security private data. Public and
                    private data must be specified using corresponding custom
                    attributes. (opposite option is -eva-no-secure-flow)
-eva-taint-auto     Automatically taint the function parameters of user input
                    based functions (scanf, fgets, etc). (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-taint-auto)
-eva-traces-dot <FILENAME>  Output to the given filename the Cfg in dot
                    format.
-eva-traces-project  Try to convert the Cfg into a program in a new project.
                    (opposite option is -eva-no-traces-project)
-eva-traces-unify-loop  Specify if all the instances of a loop should try to
                    share theirs traces. (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-traces-unify-loop)
-eva-traces-unroll-loop  Specify if the traces domain should unroll the
                    loops. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -eva-no-traces-unroll-loop)

*** DEBUG

-eva-debug <n>      level of debug for plug-in Eva (default to 0)

*** DETERMINISTIC PROGRAMS

-eva-interpreter-mode  Stop at first call to a library function, if main()
                    has arguments, on undecided branches (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-interpreter-mode)
-eva-stop-at-nth-alarm <n>  Abort the analysis when the nth alarm is emitted.

*** DYNAMIC ALLOCATION

-eva-alloc-builtin <imprecise|by_stack|fresh|fresh_weak>  Select the behavior
                    of allocation builtins. By default, they use up to
                    [-eva-mlevel] bases for each callstack (<by_stack>). They
                    can also use one <imprecise> base for all allocations,
                    create a <fresh> strong base at each call, or create a
                    <fresh_weak> base at each call. (preferably use
                    -eva-alloc-builtin="imprecise|by_stack|fresh|fresh_weak")
-eva-alloc-functions <f1,...,fn>  Control call site creation for dynamically
                    allocated bases. Dynamic allocation builtins use the call
                    sites of malloc/calloc/realloc to know where to create
                    new bases. This detection does not work for custom
                    allocators or wrappers on top of them, unless they are
                    listed here. By default, contains malloc, calloc and
                    realloc. (preferably use
                    -eva-alloc-functions="f1,...,fn")
-eva-malloc-functions <f1,...,fn>  alias for option -eva-alloc-functions
-eva-alloc-returns-null  Memory allocation built-ins (malloc, calloc,
                    realloc) are modeled as nondeterministically returning a
                    null pointer (set by default, opposite option is
                    -eva-no-alloc-returns-null)
-eva-mlevel <m>     Set to [m] the number of precise dynamic allocations
                    besides the initial one, for each callstack (defaults to
                    0)

*** GETTING INFORMATION

-eva-help           help of plug-in Eva
-eva-h              alias for option -eva-help

*** INITIAL CONTEXT

-eva-context-depth <n>  Use <n> as the depth of the default context for Eva.
                    (defaults to 2)
-eva-context-valid-pointers  Only allocate valid pointers until
                    context-depth, and then use NULL (defaults to false)
                    (opposite option is -eva-no-context-valid-pointers)
-eva-context-width <n>  Use <n> as the width of the default context for Eva.
                    (defaults to 2)
-eva-initialization-padding-globals <yes|no|maybe>  Specify how padding bits
                    are initialized inside global variables. Possible values
                    are <yes> (padding is fully initialized), <no> (padding
                    is completely uninitialized), or <maybe> (padding may be
                    uninitialized). Default is <yes>.

*** OUTPUT MESSAGES

-eva-annot <f>      Populate the specified functions with assertions
                    representing the range of values computed by Eva on
                    l-values read by the code, when available. (preferably
                    use -eva-annot="f")
-eva-flamegraph <file>  Dump a summary of the time spent analyzing function
                    calls in a format suitable for the Flamegraph tool
                    (http://www.brendangregg.com/flamegraphs.html)
-eva-log <K_1:file_1,...>  copy log messages from Eva to a file. <K> is a
                    combination of these characters:
                    a: ALL messages (equivalent to 'dfiruw')
                    d: debug       e: user or internal error (same as 'iu')
                    f: feedback    i: internal error
                    r: result      u: user error    w: warning
                    An empty <K> (e.g. ":file.txt") defaults to 'iruw'. One
                    plug-in can output to several files and vice-versa.
                    (preferably use -eva-log="K_1:file_1,...")
-eva-msg-key <k1[,...,kn]>  enables message display for categories
                    <k1>,...,<kn>. Use -eva-msg-key help to get a list of
                    available categories, and * to enable all categories
                    (preferably use -eva-msg-key="k1[,...,kn]")
-eva-print-callstacks  When printing a message, also show the current call
                    stack (opposite option is -eva-no-print-callstacks)
-eva-report-red-statuses <filename>  Output the list of "red properties" in a
                    csv file of the given name. These are the properties
                    which were invalid for some states. Their consolidated
                    status may not be invalid, but they should often be
                    investigated first.
-eva-show-perf      Compute and show a summary of the time spent analyzing
                    function calls (opposite option is -eva-no-show-perf)
-eva-show-slevel <n>  Period for showing consumption of the allotted slevel
                    during analysis
-eva-statistics-file <file.csv>  Dump some internal statistics about the
                    analysis
-eva-verbose <n>    level of verbosity for plug-in Eva (default to 5)
-eva-warn-key <k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]>  set warning status for category <k1>
                    to <s1>,...,<kn> to <sn>. Use -eva-warn-key help to get a
                    list of available categories, and * to enable all
                    categories. Possible statuses are inactive, feedback,
                    warning, error, abort, feedback-once, warning-once,
                    error-once. Defaults to warning. (preferably use
                    -eva-warn-key="k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]")

*** PRECISION VS. TIME

-eva-auto-loop-unroll <n>  Limit of the automatic loop unrolling: all loops
                    whose number of iterations can be easily bounded by <n>
                    are completely unrolled.
-eva-builtin <f:ffc>  When analyzing function <f>, try to use Frama-C builtin
                    <ffc> instead. Fall back to <f> if <ffc> cannot handle
                    its arguments. (preferably use -eva-builtin="f:ffc")
-eva-builtins-auto  When set, builtins will be used automatically to replace
                    known C functions (set by default, opposite option is
                    -eva-no-builtins-auto)
-eva-builtins-list  List existing builtins, and which functions they are
                    automatically associated to (if any)
-eva-default-loop-unroll <n>  Define the default limit for loop unroll
                    annotations that do not explicitly provide a limit.
-eva-enumerate-cond  Activate reduce_by_cond_enumerate. (set by default,
                    opposite option is -eva-no-enumerate-cond)
-eva-ilevel <n>     Sets of integers are represented as sets up to <n>
                    elements. Above, intervals with congruence information
                    are used (defaults to 8, must be above 2)
-eva-interprocedural-history  Keep partitioning history through function
                    returns (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-interprocedural-history)
-eva-interprocedural-splits  Keep partitioning splits through function
                    returns (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-interprocedural-splits)
-eva-memexec        Speed up analysis by not recomputing functions already
                    analyzed in the same context. Callstacks for which the
                    analysis has not been recomputed are incorrectly shown as
                    dead in the GUI. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -eva-no-memexec)
-eva-min-loop-unroll <n>  Unroll <n> loop iterations for each loop,
                    regardless of the slevel settings and the number of
                    states already propagated. Can be overwritten on a
                    case-by-case basis by loop unroll annotations.
-eva-oracle-depth <n>  Maximum number of successive uses of the oracle by the
                    domain for the evaluation of an expression. Set 0 to
                    disable the oracle.
-eva-partition-history <n>  Keep states distinct as long as the <n> last
                    branching in their traces are also distinct. (A value of
                    0 deactivates this feature)
-eva-partition-history-function <f:n>  Override partition-history with <n>
                    when analyzing <f> (preferably use
                    -eva-partition-history-function="f:n")
-eva-partition-value <V>  Partition the space of reachable states according
                    to the possible values of the global(s) variable(s) V.
                    (preferably use -eva-partition-value="V")
-eva-plevel <n>     Use <n> as the precision level for arrays accesses. Array
                    accesses are precise as long as the interval for the
                    index contains less than n values. (defaults to 200)
-eva-reduction-depth <n>  Maximum number of successive backward reductions
                    that the domain may initiate.
-eva-remove-redundant-alarms  After the analysis, try to remove redundant
                    alarms, so that the user needs to inspect fewer of them
                    (set by default, opposite option is
                    -eva-no-remove-redundant-alarms)
-eva-skip-stdlib-specs  Skip ACSL specifications on functions originating
                    from the standard library of Frama-C, when their bodies
                    are evaluated (set by default, opposite option is
                    -eva-no-skip-stdlib-specs)
-eva-slevel <n>     Superpose up to <n> states when unrolling control flow.
                    The larger n, the more precise and expensive the analysis
                    (defaults to 0)
-eva-slevel-function <f:n>  Override slevel with <n> when analyzing <f>
                    (preferably use -eva-slevel-function="f:n")
-eva-slevel-merge-after-loop <f | @all>  When set, the different execution
                    paths that originate from the body of a loop are merged
                    before entering the next execution. (preferably use
                    -eva-slevel-merge-after-loop="f | @all")
-eva-split-limit <N>  Prevent split annotations or -eva-partition-value from
                    enumerating more than N cases
-eva-split-return <full|auto|N>  Control the propagation of states separated
                    by option -eva-slevel at the return of a function. By
                    default, all inferred states at a return point are joined
                    into one single state, which is fast but imprecise. With
                    'full', all inferred states are propagated back to the
                    callsite, which is costly but precise. With 'auto',
                    states inferred at a return point are automatically
                    joined or kept separate according to the function return
                    code. With a number <N>, keep states distinct only
                    according to the value of the predicate \result == N.
-eva-split-return-function <f:full|f:auto|f:N|f:>  Override the global option
                    -eva-split-return at the return of function <f>. <f:>
                    reverts to the the default strategy where all states are
                    joined at the return point of <f>. (preferably use
                    -eva-split-return-function="f:full|f:auto|f:N|f:")
-eva-subdivide-non-linear <n>  Improve precision when evaluating expressions
                    in which a variable appears multiple times, by splitting
                    its value at most n times. Defaults to 0.
-eva-subdivide-non-linear-function <f:n>  Override the global option
                    -eva-subdivide-non-linear with <n>when analyzing the
                    function <f>. (preferably use
                    -eva-subdivide-non-linear-function="f:n")
-eva-unroll-recursive-calls <n>  Unroll <n> recursive calls before using the
                    specification of the recursive function to interpret the
                    calls.
-eva-use-spec <f1,..,fn>  Use the ACSL specification of the functions instead
                    of their definitions (preferably use
                    -eva-use-spec="f1,..,fn")
-eva-widening-delay <n>  Do not widen before the <n>-th iteration (defaults
                    to 3)
-eva-widening-period <n>  After the first widening, widen each <n> iterations
                    (defaults to 2)

*** PROPAGATION AND ALARMS 

-eva-initialized-locals  Local variables enter in scope fully initialized.
                    Only useful for the analysis of programs buggy w.r.t.
                    initialization. (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-initialized-locals)
-eva-reduce-on-logic-alarms  Force reductions by a predicate to ignore logic
                    alarms emitted while the predicate is evaluated
                    (experimental) (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-reduce-on-logic-alarms)
-eva-undefined-pointer-comparison-propagate-all  If the target program
                    appears to contain undefined pointer comparisons,
                    propagate both outcomes {0; 1} in addition to the
                    emission of an alarm (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-undefined-pointer-comparison-propagate-all)
-eva-warn-copy-indeterminate <f | @all>  Warn when a statement copies a value
                    that may be indeterminate (uninitialized, containing an
                    escaping address, or infinite/NaN floating-point value).
                    Set by default; can be deactivated for function 'f' by
                    '=-f', or for all functions by '=-@all'. (preferably use
                    -eva-warn-copy-indeterminate="f | @all")
-eva-warn-pointer-subtraction  Warn when subtracting two pointers that may
                    not be in the same allocated block, and return the
                    pointwise difference between the offsets. When unset, do
                    not warn but generate imprecise offsets. (set by default,
                    opposite option is -eva-no-warn-pointer-subtraction)
-eva-warn-signed-converted-downcast  Signed downcasts are decomposed into two
                    operations: a conversion to the signed type of the
                    original width, then a downcast. Warn when the downcast
                    may exceed the destination range. (opposite option is
                    -eva-no-warn-signed-converted-downcast)
-eva-warn-undefined-pointer-comparison <all|pointer|none>  Warn on all
                    pointer comparisons, on comparisons where the arguments
                    have pointer type (default), or never warn

*** RESULTS MEMOIZATION VS. TIME

-eva-join-results   Precompute consolidated states once Eva is computed (set
                    by default, opposite option is -eva-no-join-results)
-eva-no-results-domain <domains>  Do not record the states of some domains
                    during the analysis. (preferably use
                    -eva-no-results-domain="domains")
-eva-no-results-function <f>  Do not record the values obtained for the
                    statements of function f (preferably use
                    -eva-no-results-function="f")
-eva-results        Record values for each of the statements of the program.
                    (set by default, opposite option is -eva-no-results)
